    {
      "id": "f376e292721bf560d9adb0eb6173a8eb39a69987",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-09-06 22:02:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.4/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/a0ddfe4c-1735-11e3-8c83-52540035b04c).  Ran 14 tests.  1 tests failed: sanity-hsm.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2020736f40b48226ae65fead6163ce656008ee63",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-06 23:25:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Could you also apply your mask to RELEASE?\n\nI had hoped to but it's implementation doesn't fit in with the other request types and so I decided to push it as is. We can follow on with a change to bring release into the same /proc interface and to implement Thomas' suggestion.\n\n> Forbid request like archive for read-only but accepting restore is strange... What the exact philosophy behind that?\n\nThe principle of least privilege.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d5ebb1ab93e316ff902771b62efb6eb386d50b1b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 140,
        "name": "jacques-Charles Lafoucriere",
        "email": "jacques-charles.lafoucriere@cea.fr",
        "username": "jcl"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-09 11:10:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (5 inline comments)\n\n- for release, we can send an RPC RELEASE action just to check if it is allowed on not on MDT\n- This is not only related to this patch but I think we have to prepare a patch for 2.4.X to be HSM compatible (and to define what does it mean)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "21512351bbcd7cd8556833cf284b0756b6cb586c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-10 13:45:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> for release, we can send an RPC RELEASE action just to check if it is allowed on not on MDT\n\n> This is not only related to this patch but I think we have to prepare a patch for 2.4.X to be HSM compatible (and to define what does it mean)\n\nNow a 2.4 client cannot release files. I do not think this is a huge issue in itself. But with the permission checking issue and the lingering LDLM issues around release, I think that all requests (including release) should go through the coordinator and to the agent. Assuming that the copytool has a dedicated mount point which avoids the chaos of a normal lustre client then LDLM issues should be mitigated. Moreover the 2.4 client will be more easily supported.\n\nIs it too late for such a change?\n\nIn any case we need to ensure that the 2.4 client is packing the correct suppgids (or -1) for the HSM RPCs.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c73164376232f724bdef3cbc075f0976063a4640",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 217,
        "name": "Aurelien Degremont",
        "email": "aurelien.degremont@cea.fr",
        "username": "adegremont",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-09-11 08:12:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> This is not only related to this patch but I think we have to prepare a patch for 2.4.X to be HSM compatible (and to define what does it mean)\n\n>Now a 2.4 client cannot release files. I do not think this is a huge issue in itself.\n\nThat's fine I think.\n\n>But with the permission checking issue and the lingering LDLM issues around release, I think that all requests (including release) should go through the coordinator and to the agent.\n\nI do not link this idea. So far, all requests except release go through coordinator and eventually to the agent (except for cancel).\nSo this is already the case except for Release.\n\nThis is big change and scalability drawback to have release go that way. What's the benefit? I really prefer we do not do that.\n\n> Assuming that the copytool has a dedicated mount point which avoids the chaos of a normal lustre client then LDLM issues should be mitigated. Moreover the 2.4 client will be more easily supported.\n\nI do not see what you mean.\n\n\nPlease not that release will be done by the Robinhood node, mostly, which will be a Lustre 2.5 client. There is the same requirement on Robinhood node and agent node.\n\n\n>In any case we need to ensure that the 2.4 client is packing the correct suppgids (or -1) for the HSM RPCs.\n\nWe could extract the client side part of your patch and apply it to 2.4",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
